<subSubSection id="22A66546FFA7FFEBFF41FA714A23FA58" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFA7FFEBFF41FA714A23FA58" blockId="63.[151,1436,1287,2033]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFA7FFEBFF41FA714A45FA75" bold="true" box="[199,326,1468,1493]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is an adjective and refers to the microhabitat in which this species was found (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="22A66546FFA7FFEBFF41F9C949C8F955" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFA7FFEBFF41F9C949C8F955" blockId="63.[151,1436,1287,2033]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFA7FFEBFF41F9C94A39F9BD" bold="true" box="[199,314,1540,1565]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Males are easily distinguished from all other known pholcids by armature of male chelicerae (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFA7FFEBFAECF9C94BFCF9E0" captionStart="FIGURES 249–251" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1505,1527]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,340,1477]" captionTargetId="figure@66.[151,1436,339,1484]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 249–251. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (ZFMK, Ar 20647). 249–250. Male chelicerae, frontal and lateral views. 251. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view. pp, pore plate. Scale lines: 0.2." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619116/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 249–250</figureCitation>
): proximal frontal processes with dense brushes of hairs with short but strong side branches; also by shape of procursus (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFA7FFEBFEB2F9814AD4F9C4" box="[308,471,1612,1637]" captionStart="FIGURES 246–248" captionStartId="65.[151,264,1512,1534]" captionTargetBox="[159,1432,190,1491]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[151,1436,179,1491]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURES 246–248. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (ZFMK, Ar 20647). 246. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 247–248. Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. ba, bulbal apophysis; gb, genital bulb; pr, procursus. Scale lines: 0.3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619114/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 246, 248</figureCitation>
): very simple, distally weakly sclerotized and curved towards prolateral. The ZFMK has a very similar undescribed species with much smaller but otherwise identical pedipalps (femur length 0.26– 0.28 versus 0.40), shorter cheliceral apophyses, and longer and thinner legs (tibia 1 L/d 85 versus 55). Females of 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFA7FFEBFF11F9744A3AF970" box="[151,313,1721,1744]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="itaguyrussu">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFA7FFEBFF11F9744A3AF970" box="[151,313,1721,1744]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">P. itaguyrussu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFA7FFEBFEFEF974492AF970" box="[376,553,1719,1744]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ybytyriguara">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFA7FFEBFEFEF974492AF970" box="[376,553,1719,1744]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">P. ybytyriguara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown; females of undescribed species in ZFMK differ by shape of epigynum (compare 
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFA7FFEBFEF8F911491BF955" box="[382,536,1756,1781]" captionStart="FIGURES 240–245" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 240–245. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs 243–245</figureCitation>
with 252–263).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="22A66546FFA7FF95FF41F9324A31F84E" lastPageId="65" lastPageNumber="66" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFA7FFEBFF41F9324FA3F8C0" blockId="63.[151,1436,1287,2033]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFA7FFEBFF41F9324A9CF8B8" bold="true" box="[199,415,1791,1816]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus id="B507886FFFA7FFEBFE36F932491BF8B8" box="[432,536,1791,1816]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">holotype</typeStatus>
). MEASUREMENTS. Total length 3.5, carapace width 0.95. Distance PME-PME 50 µm; diameter PME 110 µm; distance PME-ALE 70 µm; distance AME-AME 10 µm, diameter AME 15 µm. Leg 1: 18.0 (4.2 + 0.3 + 4.4 + 7.7 + 1.4), tibia 2: 2.8, tibia 3: 2.1, tibia 4: 2.7; tibia 1 L/d: 55.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFA7FFEBFF41F8A14FADF851" blockId="63.[151,1436,1287,2033]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">COLOR (in ethanol). Carapace pale ochre with brown median band including ocular area and brown lateral bands; clypeus brown; sternum light brown with some light spots; legs light brown with darker rings on femora (subdistal) and tibiae (proximal and subdistal). Abdomen pale greenish, with bluish marks dorsally and laterally; ventrally with light brown plate in front of gonopore and dark median band behind gonopore.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD8FF94FF41FF554AEBFF58" blockId="64.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
BODY. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFD8FF94FE28FF5A4948FF10" box="[430,587,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 240–245" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 240–245. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 241–242</figureCitation>
. Ocular area slightly raised. Thoracic furrow shallow but distinct in anterior part. Clypeus unmodified. Sternum wider than long (0.60/0.46), unmodified. Gonopore in very posterior position (at ~70% of abdomen length).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD8FF94FF41FEC94826FEE0" blockId="64.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
CHELICERAE. As in 
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFD8FF94FE2AFEC9494AFEBD" box="[428,585,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 249–251" captionStartId="66.[151,264,1505,1527]" captionTargetBox="[185,1402,340,1477]" captionTargetId="figure@66.[151,1436,339,1484]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 249–251. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (ZFMK, Ar 20647). 249–250. Male chelicerae, frontal and lateral views. 251. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view. pp, pore plate. Scale lines: 0.2." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619116/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 249–250</figureCitation>
, with distinctive pair of frontal apophyses curved downwards and set with dense brushes of hairs with short but strong side branches.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD8FF94FF41FE804E17FE70" blockId="64.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
PALPS. As in 
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFD8FF94FEF5FE814914FEC5" box="[371,535,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 246–248" captionStartId="65.[151,264,1512,1534]" captionTargetBox="[159,1432,190,1491]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[151,1436,179,1491]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURES 246–248. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (ZFMK, Ar 20647). 246. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 247–248. Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. ba, bulbal apophysis; gb, genital bulb; pr, procursus. Scale lines: 0.3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619114/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Figs 246–248</figureCitation>
; coxa relatively large (i.e. palp small relative to body size), with rounded retrolateral apophysis, trochanter barely modified, femur with retrolateral-ventral process proximally and distinct ventral apophysis distally; tarsus with 3–4 macrosetae; procursus simple, distally weakly sclerotized, widened, and curved towards prolateral; bulb large, with whitish protrusion dorsally and flat distal bulbal apophysis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD8FF94FF41FE104A49FD9D" blockId="64.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">LEGS. Without spines, few vertical hairs; with curved hairs on legs 2 only (tibiae and metatarsi); retrolateral trichobothrium of tibia 1 at 6%; prolateral trichobothrium present on all tibiae; tarsus 1 with ~20 pseudosegments, distally distinct.</paragraph>
<caption id="3EC36645FFD8FF94FF11F8A74E05F863" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" startId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" targetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" targetPageId="64">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD8FF94FF11F8A74E05F863" blockId="64.[151,1436,1898,1987]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD8FF94FF11F8A74A6CF820" bold="true" box="[151,367,1898,1920]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">FIGURES 240–245.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD8FF94FEFFF8A74983F820" authority="Huber &amp; Carvalho, 2019" authorityName="Huber &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="2019" box="[377,640,1898,1920]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bromelicolus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD8FF94FEFFF8A74983F820" box="[377,640,1898,1920]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Psilochorus bromelicolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD8FF94FD0EF8A749C7F820" bold="true" box="[648,708,1898,1920]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="43FB57A4FFD8FF94FD0EF8A749C7F820" box="[648,708,1898,1920]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="3EC36645FFD9FF95FF11FA254E9FF9BC" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619114/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" startId="65.[151,264,1512,1534]" targetBox="[159,1432,190,1491]" targetPageId="65">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD9FF95FF11FA254E9FF9BC" blockId="65.[151,1437,1512,1564]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FF11FA254A6DFA5E" bold="true" box="[151,366,1512,1534]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">FIGURES 246–248.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FEF0FA254979FA5E" authority="Huber &amp; Carvalho, 2019" authorityName="Huber &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="2019" box="[374,634,1512,1534]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bromelicolus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FEF0FA254979FA5E" box="[374,634,1512,1534]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Psilochorus bromelicolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FD04FA2549BEFA5E" bold="true" box="[642,701,1512,1534]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="43FB57A4FFD9FF95FD04FA2549BEFA5E" box="[642,701,1512,1534]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(ZFMK, Ar 20647). 246. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 247–248. Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. ba, bulbal apophysis; gb, genital bulb; pr, procursus. Scale lines: 0.3.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD9FF95FF41F984492EF926" blockId="65.[151,1436,1609,2030]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FF41F9844A07F9C2" bold="true" box="[199,260,1609,1634]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Male</emphasis>
(variation). Tibia 
<quantity id="AD449B28FFD9FF95FE5CF987490AF9C2" box="[474,521,1609,1634]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
4 other males: 3.7, 3.8, 4.2, 4.3. Abdomen length unusually variable (shortest abdomen 67% of longest abdomen).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD9FF95FF41F95C4AC3F89A" blockId="65.[151,1436,1609,2030]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FF41F95C4A1DF90A" bold="true" box="[199,286,1681,1706]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Female</emphasis>
. In general similar to male (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFD9FF95FDD9F95C49BCF90A" box="[607,703,1681,1706]" captionStart="FIGURES 240–245" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 240–245. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 240</figureCitation>
) but without curved hairs on legs. Tibia 
<quantity id="AD449B28FFD9FF95FB0DF95F4FB4F90A" box="[1163,1207,1681,1706]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
<specimenCount id="7CBAFD44FFD9FF95FB38F95F4E3DF90A" box="[1214,1342,1681,1706]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="female">12 females</specimenCount>
: 2.8–3.3 (mean 3.1). Epigynum simple plate (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFD9FF95FDC7F97849A5F96E" box="[577,678,1717,1742]" captionStart="FIGURES 240–245" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 240–245. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Fig. 243</figureCitation>
), anteriorly evenly curved, posteriorly slightly pointed, with dark posterior margins interrupted medially by small whitish area; pair of internal structures and median ‘receptacle’ visible through cuticle. Internal genitalia with distinct median ‘receptacle’ and pair of lateral sclerites; pore plates apparently fused medially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFD9FF95FF41F8884A31F84E" blockId="65.[151,1436,1609,2030]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FF41F8884A09F8FE" bold="true" box="[199,266,1861,1886]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Notes</emphasis>
. This species shares two potential synapomorphies with 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FC26F88B4F41F8FD" box="[928,1090,1862,1885]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="itaguyrussu">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FC26F88B4F41F8FD" box="[928,1090,1862,1885]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">P. itaguyrussu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FBF8F88B4E2DF8FE" box="[1150,1326,1861,1886]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ybytyriguara">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FBF8F88B4E2DF8FE" box="[1150,1326,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">P. ybytyriguara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and with males and females of undescribed species: (1) genital bulb with whitish protrusion dorsally (also present in the distantly related genus 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FE20F8434832F806" authority="Gonzalez-Sponga, 1998" authorityName="Gonzalez-Sponga" authorityYear="1998" box="[422,817,1933,1958]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Carapoia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FE20F8434912F805" box="[422,529,1934,1957]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Carapoia</emphasis>
González-Sponga, 1998
</taxonomicName>
); (2) pore plates more or less clearly fused medially (unknown in 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FEA9F87F4ACCF869" box="[303,463,1970,1993]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="itaguyrussu">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FEA9F87F4ACCF869" box="[303,463,1970,1993]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">P. itaguyrussu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FD8EF87F49B5F86A" box="[520,694,1969,1994]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Psilochorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ybytyriguara">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FD8EF87F49B5F86A" box="[520,694,1969,1994]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">P. ybytyriguara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; also present in some distantly related taxa, e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="ADBC4D4EFFD9FF95FB6DF87F4A24F84E" authority="Huber, 2000" authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Litoporus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lopez">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFD9FF95FB6DF87F4E9FF86A" box="[1259,1436,1969,1994]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Litoporus lopez</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="0E2D4B3CFFD9FF95FF11F8184A24F84E" author="Huber, B. A." box="[151,295,2005,2030]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="22A66546FFDAFF96FF41FF5A497BFEBD" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFDAFF96FF41FF5A4E9FFF74" blockId="66.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFDAFF96FF41FF5A4A5AFF10" bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Distribution</emphasis>
. Known from 
<typeStatus id="B507886FFFDAFF96FE78FF55492DFF10" box="[510,558,152,176]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">type</typeStatus>
locality only (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFDAFF96FD57FF5A4836FF10" box="[721,821,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 348" captionStartId="92.[151,250,917,939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,896]" captionTargetId="figure@92.[151,1436,193,896]" captionTargetPageId="92" captionText="FIGURE 348. Known distribution of Psilochorus in the Atlantic Forest of Brazil. Red marks: undescribed species (L.S. Carvalho, B.A. Huber, unpubl. data). Five further South American nominal species are currently assigned to Psilochorus, but their identities and affinities are dubious (see text)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619166/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 348</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="58C8EADFFFDAFF96FF41FF714A7EFF75" bold="true" box="[199,381,188,213]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Natural history</emphasis>
. The spiders were collected on bromeliads approximately 
<quantity id="AD449B28FFDAFF96FB88FF714F56FF74" box="[1038,1109,188,212]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 m</quantity>
above the ground (
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFDAFF96FAABFF714E93FF74" box="[1325,1424,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 336–341" captionStartId="88.[151,264,1639,1661]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1618]" captionTargetId="figure@88.[151,1436,193,1618]" captionTargetPageId="88" captionText="FIGURES 336–341. Selection of collecting sites and habitats. 336. Forest above Mokwam (West Papua), type locality of Arnapa arfak sp. n. and Aetana mokwam sp. n. 337. Tinoor Fall near Tomohon (North Sulawesi), type locality of Arnapa tinoor sp. n. 338. Entrance to Caverna Porco do Mato II (Rio Grande do Norte), type locality of Pinocchio barauna sp. n. 339. Desert between Sur and Kamil (Oman), type locality of Magana velox sp. n. 340. Bromeliad at Reserva Particular do Patrimônio Nacional Serra Bonita (Bahia), type locality of Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (note pair of spiders among leaves). 341. Disturbed forest near Sofifi (Halmahera), type locality of Giloloa sofifi sp. n. and Panjange togutil sp. n." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619152/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 340</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFDAFF96FF11FF124E9FFF58" blockId="66.[151,1436,151,285]" box="[151,1436,223,248]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Their small webs were hidden deep among the leaf bases. Males and females were sometimes found close together</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A0336CDFFDAFF96FF11FEC9497BFEBD" blockId="66.[151,1436,151,285]" box="[151,632,260,285]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
(
<figureCitation id="F2872A48FFDAFF96FF19FEC94A01FEBC" box="[159,258,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 240–245" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,625,1877]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 240–245. Psilochorus bromelicolus sp. n. (242–245: ZFMK, Ar 20647). 240–241. Live specimens; male (with short abdomen) and female with egg sac sharing web, and male (with long abdomen). 242. Male, dorsal view. 243. Epigynum, ventral view. 244–245. Cleared female genitalia, ventral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 1.0 (242), 0.2 (243–245)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2619112/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 240</figureCitation>
). One egg-sac contained 
<specimenCount id="7CBAFD44FFDAFF96FD9DFEC94976FEBD" box="[539,629,260,285]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="egg">13 eggs</specimenCount>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
